(1508, 5, '2009-06-17 22:45:10', '2009-06-18 02:45:10', 'Where will you be?\r\n<h3>2009</h3>\r\n<strong>July 22</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 6:39. India. China. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<h3>2010</h3>\r\n<strong>January 15</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Indian Ocean. Landfall in East Africa &amp; Burma.\r\n\r\n<strong>July 11</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 5:20. South Pacific Ocean. Landfall through The Cook Islands, French Polynesia, Easter Island &amp; extreme southern Chili.\r\n<h3>2011</h3>\r\n<strong>January 4</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Europe. North Africa.\r\n<strong>June 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Greenland. High Arctic.\r\n<strong>July 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Southern Ocean. New Saros begins!\r\n<strong>November 25</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2012</h3>\r\n<strong>May 20</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. East China Sea. Japan, N. Pacific. Western U.S.\r\n<strong>November 13</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:02. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<h3>2013</h3>\r\n<strong>May 10</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<strong>November 3</strong> - Hybrid Eclipse (Annular/Total). Atlantic Ocean. Central Africa.\r\n<h3>2014</h3>\r\n<strong>April 29</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Australia. Southern Ocean.\r\n<strong>October 23</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. N. America.\r\n<h3>2015</h3>\r\n<strong>March 20</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:47. North Pole. Norwegian Sea.\r\n<strong>September 13</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. S. Africa. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2016</h3>\r\n<strong>March 9</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:09.  Sumatra, Borneo, Sulawesi, Pacific Ocean.\r\n<strong>September 1</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse.  Africa.  Indian Ocean.\r\n<h3>2017</h3>\r\n<strong>February 26</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Pacific. Chile. Argentina. Atlantic. Africa.\r\n<strong>August 21</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:40. United States.', 'Eclipse Calendar', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '551-revision-34', '', '', '2009-06-17 22:45:10', '2009-06-18 02:45:10', '', 551, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/551-revision-34', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1509, 5, '2009-08-06 19:07:32', '2009-08-06 23:07:32', 'Preliminary Report - Total Eclipse of 22 July 2009.  FULL report still pending....\r\n\r\n"Misty Eclipse" Video Posted <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/video/the-misty-eclipse-2">Here</a>.\r\n\r\nThe second total eclipse in China in as many years was a much better experience than the first!  But still, we were plagued with bad weather on eclipse day.  Across eastern China, thousands of chasers pulled all-nighters and bit their nails down to the skin watching the satellite images cast doom and gloom on our hopes of clear skies.  Just hours before the eclipse began, I decided there was no clear advantage to running, and we stayed at Naked Retreats in Moganshan to try our luck.  And while Shanghai was drenched with rain, and other "best sites" were completely clouded out, we experienced one of the most dramatic eclipses of the last 20 years.  Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we caught multiple glimpses of totality through holes in the sky.  The video is awesome!  Just goes to show that while clear skies is what you hope for, nature will always surprize you with its wonders.  Not what I was expecting - but completely satisfied.\r\n\r\nWatch the new video!\r\n\r\nAnd while I prepare my FULL report, check out these links:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/krisdelcourte/sets/72157621822513677/show/" target="_blank">Mr. Black Sun</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.boston.com/bigpicture/2009/07/the_longest_solar_eclipse_of_t.html" target="_blank">The Boston Globe</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://s10.photobucket.com/albums/a120/alsonwong/China%202009/?action=view&amp;current=DSC_0002Crop800.jpg" target="_blank">Alson Wong Images</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://spaceweather.com/eclipses/gallery_22jul09.htm" target="_blank">Space Weather</a>', 'The Misty Eclipse!  ', 0, 'Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we witnessed the grand Total Eclipse of 2009. Read the preliminary report.  NEW VIDEO!!!', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-misty-eclipse', '', '\nhttp://eclipseguy.dev/video/the-misty-eclipse-2', '2010-08-29 22:06:12', '2010-08-30 02:06:12', '', 0, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/?p=1509', 0, 'post', '', 3),
(1510, 5, '2009-08-05 09:54:13', '2009-08-05 13:54:13', 'Preliminary Report - Total Eclipse of 22 July 2009.\n\nI have just returned home after chasing the eclipse to China once again.  And while this trip was much better than last year\'s expedition, we were plagued with bad weather on eclipse day.  Across eastern China, thousands of chasers pulled all-nighters and bit their nails down to the skin watching the satellite images cast doom and gloom on our hopes of clear skies.  Just hours before the eclipse began, I decided there was no clear advantage to running, and we stayed at Naked Retreats in Moganshan to try our luck.  And while Shanghai was drenched with rain, and other "best sites" were completely clouded out, we experienced one of the most dramatic eclipses of the last 20 years.  Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we caught multiple glimpses of totality through holes in the sky.  The video is awesome!  Just goes to show that while clear skies is what you hope for, nature will always surprize you with its wonders.  Not what I was expecting - but completely satisfied.  \n\nWhile I prepare my images and video for the complete report, check out these links: \n\n<a href="http://http://www.theglobeandmail.com/search/?query=solar+eclipse&x=0&y=0">The Globe & Mail</a>  -  click on "Canada\'s Eclipse Chaser"\n\n\n\n\n\n', 'The Cloudy Eclipse!  ', 0, 'Through blankets of rolling mist and fog, we witnessed the grand Total Eclipse of 2009. Read the preliminary report.  ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1509-revision', '', '', '2009-08-05 09:54:13', '2009-08-05 13:54:13', '', 1509, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1509-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
