(1652, 5, '2011-07-20 16:49:31', '2011-07-20 20:49:31', 'I am currently travelling through Peru and Argentina en route to the Total Eclipse!\n\nOn 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\n<p style="text-align: center;">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif" alt="" /></p>\n\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile/Argentina where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at  35,000 feet.  This is where I will be!  It\'s my first observation from an aircraft!  Miles above the clouds, we are guaranteed a perfect view!  From this unique vantage point, we will see approximately 3:50 of Totality.\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path.jpg"></a><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1716 aligncenter" title="Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg" alt="Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English" width="450" height="375" /></a></p>\n\nIn the weeks prior to the eclipse, I will be visiting Peru for the first time.  I land in Lima - visit Puno - Lake Titicaca - then take the train through the Andes to Cuzco where I will embark on the famous Inca Trail hike up to Machu Picchu.  This spectacular trek takes three days and is one of the most intense hikes of my eclipse chasing career!  Amazing!  Then it\'s back to Lima before making my way through Buenos Aires and on to El Calafate where our eclipse flight takes off on July 11.  This is the last total eclipse until the end of 2012 so it had better be a good one!\n\nThis eclipse is now part of eclipse chasing history!!!  Read the Trip Report, see the photos and video <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/south-america-%E2%80%93-11-july-2010" target="_self">here</a>.\n\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href="http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html" target="_blank">here.</a>\n\nYou must see a Total Eclipse of the Sun from the air before you die!', 'Eclipse Chasing Again! ', 0, 'A lifetime of eclipse chasing continues this summer with a spectacular observation from 35,000 feet. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1636-autosave', '', '', '2011-07-20 16:49:31', '2011-07-20 20:49:31', '', 1636, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-autosave', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1653, 5, '2009-12-30 01:07:11', '2009-12-30 05:07:11', 'On 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at 35, 000 feet.  I have two rows booked on this flight.  Each row has two people sharing the window where the eclipse will be visible above Earth\'s western horizon.  I have one seat available in the row where the plane\'s wing will be visible.  The wing creates no blind spot for the eclipse itself, but obviously removes a portion of the sky from view.  These are the least expensive seats on the aircraft, with the "no wing" seats costing the most.  This seat is available now for 499 Euros.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.eclipse-city.com/eclipse,patagonia,10087.html"target="-blank">Eclipse City</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'ONE SEAT AVAILABLE! Eclipse Observation Flight/Patagonia/July 2010.', 0, 'I have one seat available on an exclusive eclipse observation flight from Patagonia, 11 July 2010.  Come see an eclipse with me!  Goes to the first caller!  ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1636-revision-13', '', '', '2009-12-30 01:07:11', '2009-12-30 05:07:11', '', 1636, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-revision-13', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1654, 5, '2009-12-30 01:17:30', '2009-12-30 05:17:30', 'On 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at 35, 000 feet.  I have two rows booked on this flight.  Each row has two people sharing the window where the eclipse will be visible above Earth\'s western horizon.  I have one seat available in the row where the plane\'s wing will be visible.  The wing creates no blind spot for the eclipse itself, but obviously removes a portion of the sky from view.  These are the least expensive seats on the aircraft, with the "no wing" seats costing the most.  This seat is available now for 499 Euros.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.eclipse-city.com/eclipse,patagonia,10087.html"target="-blank">Eclipse City</a>\r\n\r\nYou have to get yourself to El Calafate, Argentina, by 11 July 2010.  \r\n\r\nWith South Pacific cruises either cost-prohibitive or completely sold out, and Easter Island already packed to the rafters, this is definitely the most exciting and cost-effective option left.  And you don\'t have to worry about the weather!  This flight will travel well above any threatening clouds and we are guaranteed a spectacular observation in crystal clear skies.  \r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'ONE SEAT AVAILABLE! Eclipse Observation Flight/Patagonia/July 2010.', 0, 'I have one seat available on an exclusive eclipse observation flight from Patagonia, 11 July 2010.  Come see an eclipse with me!  Goes to the first caller!  ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1636-revision