(1722, 5, '2009-12-30 02:21:54', '2009-12-30 06:21:54', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/ase2010globe1a.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1669 aligncenter" title="ase2010globe1a" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/ase2010globe1a-300x225.jpg" alt="ase2010globe1a" width="300" height="225" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>In red the path of the Annular Eclipse.</figure>\r\n<a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_annular_eclipse_1000.jpg"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-1667 alignleft" title="2010_annular_eclipse_1000" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_annular_eclipse_1000-150x150.jpg" alt="2010_annular_eclipse_1000" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis is what you can see in the sky on 15 January 2010 if you make it to Africa or India in time. Annular Eclipses differ from Total Eclipses in many ways but are equally fascinating.\r\n\r\nI actually have to work sometimes so I have to miss this one!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/ASE2010/ASE2010.html" target="-blank">NASA Eclipse Website</a>', 'Spectacular Annular Eclipse in January 2010! ', 0, 'This is technically the longest eclipse this century!  ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1666-revision-36', '', '', '2009-12-30 02:21:54', '2009-12-30 06:21:54', '', 1666, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1666-revision-36', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1723, 5, '2009-12-30 01:35:34', '2009-12-30 05:35:34', '<p style="text-align: center;">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif" alt="" /></p>\r\n\r\nYou have to get into that little black dot!! \r\n\r\nThis is the next major Total Eclipse to come to Earth.  It is visible almost entirely from the Pacific Ocean ONLY!  It makes landfall on a few, remote islands near Tahiti - and on Easter Island, of all places.  Many cruises to see totality have been planned and many are already fully booked.  This is an expensive eclipse to chase because of the difficult location. But what is money for?  I am booked on a private charter aircraft out of Argentina that will fly into the eclipse at 35,000 feet!  We are guaranteed clear skies!  And I have one seat available right now if you want to join this expedition.  <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/news/one-seat-available-eclipse-observation-flightpatagoniajuly-2010">Click here for details.</a>\r\n\r\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href="http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html"target="-blank">here.</a>  \r\n\r\n ', 'Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010', 0, 'This is the next big one! ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1521-revision-20', '', '', '2009-12-30 01:35:34', '2009-12-30 05:35:34', '', 1521, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1521-revision-20', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1724, 5, '2009-09-08 17:33:09', '2009-09-08 21:33:09', 'TED is a small non-profit organization dedicated to Ideas Worth Spreading.  They invite speakers from around the world to give talks on virtually every topic and then make the videos available on the web for all to see.  The website features hundreds of inspired talks from the likes of Al Gore and Tony Robbins.  \r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.ted.com/"target="-blank">http://www.ted.com</a>\r\n\r\nTEDx events are local, independently organized TED events that bring people and ideas together in local communities.  The Toronto TEDx Event is Thursday September 10, and I have been asked to give one of the three-minute talks on what I have learned from my eclipse chasing! \r\n\r\nWatch live on September 10 between 3:30 and 4pm EDT to see my talk live.  After this time, it will be available on the TEDx Toronto website.  \r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.tedxto.com/"target="-blank">http://www.tedxto.com</a>', 'Eclipseguy Speaks at TED', 0, 'Watch live on the web Thursday September 10 - or stream the talk from the archive later! ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1583-revision-6', '', '', '2009-09-08 17:33:09', '2009-09-08 21:33:09', '', 1583, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1583-revision-6', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1725, 5, '2009-09-08 17:38:39', '2009-09-08 21:38:39', 'Preliminary Report - Total Eclipse of 22 July 2009.\r\n\r\nNew Video Posted <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/video/the-misty-eclipse-2">Here</a>.\r\n\r\nI have just returned home after chasing the eclipse to China once again.  And while this trip was much better than last year\'s expedition, we were plagued with bad weather on eclipse day.  Across eastern China, thousands of chasers pulled all-nighters and bit their nails down to the skin watching the satellite images cast doom and gloom on our hopes of clear skies.  Just hours before the eclipse began, I decided there was no clear advantage to running, and we stayed at Naked Retreats in Moganshan to try our luck.  And while Shanghai was drenched with rain, and other "best sites" were completely clouded out, we experienced one of the most dramatic eclipses of the last 20 years.  Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we caught multiple glimpses of totality through holes in the sky.  The video is awesome!  Just goes to show that while clear skies is what you hope for, nature will always surprize you with its wonders.  Not what I was expecting - but completely satisfied.  \r\n\r\nWatch the new video!\r\n\r\nAnd while I prepare my complete report, check out these links: \r\n\r\nSam Beattie from Agence France-Presse followed me to Moganshan for the eclipse and filed this video report: \r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.theglobeandmail.com/video/canadas-eclipse-chaser/article1227034/"target="-blank">The Globe & Mail</a>\r\n\r\nOther images from across the eclipse path: \r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/krisdelcourte/sets/72157621822513677/show/"target="-blank">Mr. Black Sun</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.boston.com/bigpicture/2009/07/the_longest_solar_eclipse_of_t.html"target="-blank">The Boston Globe</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://s10.photobucket.com/albums/a120/alsonwong/China%202009/?action=view&current=DSC_0002Crop800.jpg"target="-blank">Alson Wong Images</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://spaceweather.com/eclipses/gallery_22jul09.htm"target="-blank">Space Weather</a>\r\n', 'The Misty Eclipse!  ', 0, 'Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we witnessed the grand Total Eclipse of 2009. Read the preliminary report.  NEW VIDEO!!!', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1509-revision-19', '', '', '2009-09-08 17:38:39', '2009-09-08 21:38:39', '', 1509, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1509-revision-19', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1726, 5, '2009-06-12 21:52:21', '2009-06-13 01:52:21', 'Check out this recent article by Richard Madden on the upcoming eclipse in China.Â  Madden writes for the Telegraph in the U.K.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/festivalsandevents/5437964/Chinas-solar-eclipse-Feel-the-power-of-the-dark-side.html" target="-blank">The Power of the Dark Side</a>', 'The Power of the Dark Side', 0, 'Recent article on the upcoming eclipse in China by Richard Madden for the Telegraph in the U.K. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1425-revision-3', '', '', '2009-06-12 21:52:21', '2009-06-13 01:52:21', '', 1425, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1425-revision-3', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1727, 5, '2009-08-06 18:37:43', '2009-08-06 22:37:43', 'The shadow of the Moon visits Earth next on 22 July 2009.\r\n\r\nWhere will you be?Â  Sitting at home?Â  At work?Â  Wasting time watching TV?\r\n\r\nForget all that.Â  Book a flight to Shanghai right now.Â  Come and see your first Total Solar Eclipse.\r\n<figure><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/TSE2009globe_400.jpg" alt="TSE2009_globe" />\r\nThe dark blue line is where you can see a Total Eclipse. Best place to see it is China.</figure>\r\n<figure><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/TSE2009_china_path.jpg" alt="TSE2009_path" />\r\n\r\nThis is the eclipse path through China.  Pick a city!  Let\'s go!\r\n\r\nImages Espenak/NASA/GSFC</figure>\r\nQuit wasting so much time.  Contact me immediately to get on an expedition - last minute!\r\n\r\n<a href="mailto:imoon@eclipseguy.staging.tunaheart.com">imoon@eclipseguy.staging.tunaheart.com</a>\r\n\r\nOr, post a comment right here!\r\n\r\nRemember:  Quit wasting your time not seeing a Total Solar Eclipse.', 'Total Solar Eclipse Only Days Away!', 0, 'Attention all readers! This is the longest TSE of this century!  You will never get this chance again!\r\nQuit wasting so much time... ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1096-revision-26', '', '', '2009-08-06 18:37:43', '2009-08-06 22:37:43', '', 1096, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1096-revision-26', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1728, 5, '2009-06-12 21:55:22', '2009-06-13 01:55:22', '<p style="text-align: justify;">MY OUTBACK ECLIPSE ADVENTURE\r\nBy eclipseguy\r\nRASC, Toronto Centre\r\nMarch 2003 Issue of SCOPE - Royal Astronomical Society of Canada\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">One of the things I love about astronomy is that it invites you to tackle some pretty intense concepts. While the nature of the universe, its composition, dimensions and behaviour are sure to kill conversation at a dinner party, I have always enjoyed the intellectual wrestling match of cosmology, and I have found myself gravitating towards people and things that stimulate this nerve.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Here in our solar system geometry is a particularly significant concept and one of my favourites. With a good working knowledge of the celestial mechanics of our Sun, planets and moons there is a lot of great astronomy available to you. Iâ€™ll never forget the moment I came to understand truly how our Moon works and how she changes her appearance so mysteriously night after night. It was a turning point in my intellectual life, and although I didnâ€™t know it at the time it was the genesis of my becoming a rabid eclipse chaser.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Now the motions of the Moon are one thing - the dynamics of its shadow are quite another. During a total eclipse of the sun it seems that for a single exclusive moment the mighty majesty of the solar system is unleashed, branded onto the Earth, making brilliantly evident the entire system that lies beyond. For me, these events are the front door into astronomy. After an eclipse, I donâ€™t need any more convincing.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Iâ€™ve done some pretty crazy things in pursuit of the shadow. Driving to within 100 kilometers of the Iraqi No-Fly Zone in southern Turkey and stomaching the seas of the Pacific Ocean off the coast of Mexico during a tropical storm are a few examples. But I think flying into the middle of the Outback in a tiny, twin-prop aircraft to camp on an airstrip pretty much takes the cake.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In the past, I have been a part of all kinds of eclipse expeditions. From solo voyages to trips with the family to groups of fifty or more RASC members enjoying two weeks together in some remote location. For the total eclipse of 04 December 2002, I convinced my friend, Matt Montgomery, a pilot living in Sydney, to fly five of us to Lyndhurst, South Australia, in an attempt to rendezvous with the shadow in one of the most unforgiving landscapes in the world.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Planning this chase took a year. A myriad of factors had to be woven into a single strategy if we were to successfully observe the eclipse and get out of there alive - two things that were essential. After narrowing down our list of potential observing sites within the path of totality to Lyndhurst, and selecting an appropriate aircraft for the task, our biggest management issue was weight. We had a team of five, camping equipment, food and water, film and video gear and a narrow ninety kilogram allowance for everything. I did my part to meet the target by eating power bars and choosing cameras not clothes!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">From Sydney, we took a leisurely three days to arrive in the eclipse zone, stopping at remote towns each night to break up the flying. In White Cliffs, we slept underground in a cave attached to an opal mine! The unique Bed &amp; Breakfast was cooled naturally by the air from the giant caverns and was completely protected from the blast-furnace heat of the desert. And this place is booked 300 days a year!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Camped beside our plane on the airstrip at Lyndhurst waiting for the eclipse, we endured two days of dry, stiff winds stirring up the red sands and dust of the desert. The wind was strong enough to force the tiny particles of dust through the tent walls and we soon learned that in addition to trying to keep the tents from collapsing, we would have to work, sleep and eat in the dust! And the harsh conditions did nothing to stop 6,000 freaky revellers from attending the Outback Eclipse Festival only a kilometer from our camp! The biggest psychedelic eclipse party ever!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Fortunately, all this did nothing to cloud the perfectly clear skies we enjoyed for the duration, allowing me get my first-ever sightings of the Magellanic Clouds. I did not know dark until I camped in the Outback.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">On eclipse day I am like a nine year-old on Christmas morning. I spent the day blissfully wound up in the anticipation of the eclipse and the intense extreme of my location. And wandering around a rave in the middle of the desert with thousands of artists and performers was an experience I will not soon forget!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">A few hours before the eclipse, we were back at our camp on the airstrip. My cameras were locked down and the clock was running. The mechanics of the solar system were working perfectly and my chances of seeing totality were now 100%.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">When it finally came it was swift and sublime. My journal recalls, â€œâ€¦this was one of the prettiest totalities I have ever seen. Electric chromosphere!â€ We were so far along the eclipse path, the angle of the shadow cone so narrow, that from inside the umbra the shadow looked like a giant set of eagles wings reaching towards me from the horizon! Incredible! I was only just beginning to believe my eyes when the diamond ring at third contact burst into the picture. My finger hit the cable release attached to my Nikon F3 just at that second. Got it! Then I saw the shadow rush away from us and up into space. Whew! What took a year to plan was over in 24 seconds. But it was the best 24 seconds of the trip. And that terrific post-eclipse glow was even better knowing I had that picture in the can.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">And there was much rejoicing. I love to party after seeing an eclipse and the Aussies know what thatâ€™s about. Chasers from all over the world joined together at the Elsewhere Hotel in Lyndhurst for a traditional Outback BBQ dinner and another terrific night under the stars.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The concepts that govern the universe might be tough to tackle but if you can get out there and watch them at work it all becomes clearer. Much more than the illusion of the two dimensional barrier known as â€œthe sky,â€ we live in a deep, dynamic system of light and mass and motion. And if you come with me next time Iâ€™ll turn you into an eclipse chaser, too.</p>', 'Article on the 2002 Outback eclipse', 0, 'Here is my submission for the March 2003 edition of SCOPE.  ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1244-revision-4', '', '', '2009-06-12 21:55:22', '2009-06-13 01:55:22', '', 1244, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1244-revision-4', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1729, 5, '2010-01-03 16:04:35', '2010-01-03 20:04:35', 'On 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif" alt="" /></p>\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at  35, 000 feet.  I have two rows booked on this flight.  Each row has two people sharing the window where the eclipse will be visible above Earth\'s western horizon.  As of 30 December 2009, I have one seat available in the row where the plane\'s wing will be visible.  The wing creates no blind spot for the eclipse itself, but obviously removes a portion of the sky from view.  These are the least expensive seats on the aircraft, with the "no wing" seats costing the most.  This seat is available now for €499/USD715. If you are interested, post a comment here or contact me by email.  This seat will not be available for long!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.eclipse-city.com/eclipse,patagonia,10087.html"target="_blank">Eclipse City</a>\r\n<a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/091218_observation-flight.pdf">Download Seating Plan</a>\r\n\r\nYou have to get yourself to El Calafate, Argentina, by 11 July 2010.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path.jpg"></a><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1716 aligncenter" title="Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg" alt="Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English" width="450" height="375" /></a></p>\r\n\r\nWith South Pacific cruises either cost-prohibitive or completely sold out, and Easter Island already packed to the rafters, this is definitely the most exciting and cost-effective option left.  And you don\'t have to worry about the weather!  This flight will travel well above any threatening clouds and we are guaranteed a spectacular observation in crystal clear skies. We will see approximately 2:55 of Totality.\r\n\r\nYou must see a Total Eclipse of the Sun from the air before you die!', 'ONE SEAT AVAILABLE! Eclipse Observation Flight/Patagonia/July 2010.', 0, 'I have one seat available on an exclusive eclipse observation flight from Patagonia, 11 July 2010.  Come see an eclipse with me!  Goes to the first caller!  ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1636-revision-32', '', '', '2010-01-03 16:04:35', '2010-01-03 20:04:35', '', 1636, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-revision-32', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
