(2298, 5, '2010-08-29 22:06:51', '2010-08-30 02:06:51', '<img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/solar_eclipse_animate_2009-jul-22.gif" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIf you were standing out in space on eclipse day - 22 July 2009 -  this is how the Total Eclipse would have looked!  That tiny black dot moving across the Earth is the only place you could see the Total Eclipse.  If you were anywhere in the broader, outer shadow - the penumbra - you would have seen a partial eclipse only.', '2009 Solar Eclipse Animation ', 0, 'See how July\'s Total Eclipse moved across the Earth. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1478-revision-20', '', '', '2010-08-29 22:06:51', '2010-08-30 02:06:51', '', 1478, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1478-revision-20', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2299, 5, '2011-07-20 14:42:15', '2011-07-20 18:42:15', 'There have been more solar eclipses in 2011 than in most years!!!!  But, alas, they are all the small ones.  In all, four partial solar eclipses grace the earthly calendar in 2011 - and not one of them as spectacular as a Total Solar Eclipse.  Partial Eclipses like this one from Oman in January...\n\n... are amazing events if you happen to be there when it happens.  But the vast majority of eclipse chasers don\'t leave home to travel the world to see them.  We save our nickels and our dimes for the big events - Total Solar Eclipses.  The next TSE is in November 2012 - visible in the South Pacific Ocean north of New Zealand - and from a tiny spot of dry land in Australia near Port Douglas along the country\'s tropical northern coast.  I have a luxurious villa already booked for this one!! (more later).\n\nBut the Next Eclipse that is drawing the attention of chasers is the Annular Solar Eclipse in May 2012.  Annular Eclipses are not quite as spectacular as TSEs - it doesn\'t get as dark - stars &amp; planets don\'t appear in the sky - and beautiful corona - the atmosphere of the sun - stays hidden from view the whole time.  But for rabid rank and file chasers who have been starved for a celestial chase sequence since July 2010 - we\'ll take what we can get.\n\nThe absence of the great coronal reveal notwithstanding, Annular Eclipses still have a lot to offer.  Much of the thrill and excitement of the chase remains intact - the spectacle in the sky is certainly very, very cool - and yet again, we get to visit a part of the globe we have never seen before.  At least, that is the case for me as the eclipse on May 20, 2012, is the first eclipse to arrive in North America in a very long time - exciting the skies over several western states near the sunset hour.  From California to Texas, the eclipse will appear over dozens of forests and National Parks, including The Grand Canyon and Monument Valley.', 'The Next Eclipse ', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2296-revision-v1', '', '', '2011-07-20 14:42:15', '2011-07-20 18:42:15', '', 2296, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/2296-revision-2', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
