inting my binoculars towards the sun and the exit pupil towards my frisbee.  May 10, 1994.</figure>\r\nIf you do plan to see this eclipse, here are a few indispensable resources to get you going:\r\n\r\nThe maps &amp; the climatology for this eclipse from <a href="http://home.cc.umanitoba.ca/~jander/ase2012/ase12intro.htm" target="_blank">Jay Anderson</a>.  Jay is the weather guru for eclipse chasers worldwide.  And - the truly awesome, interactive, Google maps for this eclipse from <a href="http://xjubier.free.fr/en/site_pages/solar_eclipses/ASE_2012_GoogleMapFull.html" target="_blank">Xavier Jubier</a>. Zoom in on the path of the eclipse - click anywhere - and see the local circumstances for the eclipse at that location.  Eclipse planning doesn\'t get any easier!\r\n\r\nWant to know more?  Post me a comment, below.', 'The Next Eclipse ', 0, 'Where are all the eclipse chasers going next? Pack your bags for May 20, 2012. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2296-revision-v1', '', '', '2011-07-20 16:25:27', '2011-07-20 20:25:27', '', 2296, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/2296-revision-25', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2330, 5, '2010-01-17 16:57:13', '2010-01-17 20:57:13', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/ase2010globe1a.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1669 aligncenter" title="ase2010globe1a" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/ase2010globe1a-300x225.jpg" alt="ase2010globe1a" width="300" height="225" /></a></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>In red the path of the Annular Eclipse.</figure>\r\n<a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_annular_eclipse_1000.jpg"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-1667 alignleft" title="2010_annular_eclipse_1000" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_annular_eclipse_1000-150x150.jpg" alt="2010_annular_eclipse_1000" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\nThis is what you would have seen in the sky on 15 January 2010 if you were anywhere in the path of annularity.  I wasn\'t - saving for July!! But thousands gathered along the eclipse path to see the millennium\'s longest eclipse.\r\n\r\nIf you missed it, here are a few links to photos and reports:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.spaceweather.com/eclipses/gallery_15jan10.htm" target="_blank">Space Weather</a>  / <a href="http://sepod.wikispaces.com/2010Jan15" target="_blank">Eclipse Chasers</a>  / <a href="http://www.sonnenfinsternis2010.de/index.htm#berichte" target="_blank">Stefan Krause</a>  / <a href="http://twitpic.com/photos/cosmos4u" target="_blank">Daniel Fischer</a>\r\n<a href="http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/ASE2010/ASE2010.html" target="_blank">NASA Eclipse Website</a>', 'Annular Eclipse on January 15 Successfully Observed!', 0, 'This was the longest eclipse for over a thousand years!! ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1666-revision-42', '', '', '2010-01-17 16:57:13', '2010-01-17 20:57:13', '', 1666, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1666-revision-42', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2331, 5, '2010-06-11 18:19:10', '2010-06-11 22:19:10', '<p style="text-align: center;">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif" alt="" /></p>\r\n\r\nYou have to get into that little black dot!!\r\n\r\nThis is the next major Total Eclipse to come to Earth.  It is visible almost entirely from the Pacific Ocean ONLY!  It makes landfall on a few, remote islands near Tahiti - and on Easter Island, of all places.  Many cruises to see totality have been planned and many are already fully booked.  This is an expensive eclipse to chase because of the difficult location. But what is money for?  I am booked on a private charter aircraft out of Argentina that will fly into the eclipse at 35,000 feet!  We are guaranteed clear skies!   <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/news/one-seat-available-eclipse-observation-flightpatagoniajuly-2010">Click here for details.</a>\r\n\r\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href="http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html" target="_blank">here.</a>', 'Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010', 0, 'This is the next big one! ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1521-revision-22', '', '', '2010-06-11 18:19:10', '2010-06-11 22:19:10', '', 1521, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1521-revision-22', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2332, 5, '2011-07-20 16:44:22', '2011-07-20 20:44:22', '<p style="text-align: center;">This was a wild and successful eclipse chase!  Read the Trip Report, see the photos &amp; video <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/south-america---11-july-2010" target="_self">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif" alt="" /></p>\r\n\r\nYou have to get into that little black dot!!\r\n\r\nThis is the next major Total Eclipse to come to Earth.  It is visible almost entirely from the Pacific Ocean ONLY!  It makes landfall on a few, remote islands near Tahiti - and on Easter Island, of all places.  Many cruises to see totality have been planned and many are already fully booked.  This is an expensive eclipse to chase because of the difficult location. But what is money for?  I am booked on a private charter aircraft out of Argentina that will fly into the eclipse at 35,000 feet!  We are guaranteed clear skies!   <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/news/one-seat-available-eclipse-observation-flightpatagoniajuly-2010">Click here for details.</a>\r\n\r\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href="http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html" target="_blank">here.</a>', 'Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010', 0, 'This is the next big one! ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1521-revision-23', '', '', '2011-07-20 16:44:22', '2011-07-20 20:44:22', '', 1521, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1521-revision-23', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2333, 5, '2010-06-24 10:36:49', '2010-06-24 14:36:49', 'I am currently travelling through Peru and Argentina en route to the Total Eclipse!\r\n\r\nOn 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif" alt="" /></p>\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile/Argentina where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at  35,000 feet.  This is where I will be!  It\'s my first observation from an aircraft!  Miles above the clouds, we are guaranteed a perfect view!  From this unique vantage point, we will see approximately 3:50 of Totality.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path.jpg"></a><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1716 aligncenter" title="Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg" alt="Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English" width="450" height="375" /></a></p>\r\n\r\nIn the weeks prior to the eclipse, I will be visiting Peru for the first time.  I land in Lima - visit Puno - Lake Titicaca - then take the train through the Andes to Cuzco where I will embark on the famous Inca Trail hike up to Machu Picchu.  This spectacular trek takes three days and is one of the most intense hikes of my eclipse chasing career!  Amazing!  Then it\'s back to Lima before making my way through Buenos Aires and on to El Calafate where our eclipse flight takes off on July 11.  This is the last total eclipse until the end of 2012 so it had better be a good one!\r\n\r\nCome back later in the summer to see all the new eclipse video and  expedition photography.\r\n\r\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href="http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html" target="_blank">here.</a>\r\n\r\nYou must see a Total Eclipse of the Sun from the air before you die!', 'Eclipse Chasing Again! ', 0, 'A lifetime of eclipse chasing continues this summer with a spectacular observation from 35,000 feet. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1636-revision-43', '', '', '2010-06-24 10:36:49', '2010-06-24 14:36:49', '', 1636, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-revision-43', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2334, 5, '2010-04-17 19:45:03', '2010-04-17 23:45:03', 'Where will you be?\r\n<h3>2010</h3>\r\n<strong>January 15</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Indian Ocean. Landfall in East Africa to Burma.  <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/news/spectacular-annular-eclipse-in-january-2010">\r\nMore.</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>July 11</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 5:20. South Pacific Ocean. Landfall through The Cook Islands, French Polynesia, Easter Island &amp; extreme southern Chili. <a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/total-solar-eclipse-of-11-july-2010">More.</a>\r\n<h3>2011</h3>\r\n<strong>January 4</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Europe. North Africa.\r\n<strong>June 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Greenland. High Arctic.\r\n<strong>July 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Southern Ocean. New Saros begins!\r\n<strong>November 25</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2012</h3>\r\n<strong>May 20</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. East China Sea. Japan, N. Pacific. Western U.S.\r\n<img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2012may20a.gif" alt="" />\r\n\r\n<strong>November 13</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:02. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2012nov13t.gif" alt="" />\r\n<h3>2013</h3>\r\n<strong>May 10</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2013may10a.gif" alt="" />\r\n\r\n<strong>November 3</strong> - Hybrid Eclipse (Annular/Total). Atlantic Ocean. Central Africa.\r\n<img src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2013nov03h.gif" alt="" />\r\n\r\n<h3>2014</h3>\r\n<strong>April 29</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Australia. Southern Ocean.\r\n<strong>October 23</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. N. America.\r\n<h3>2015</h3>\r\n<strong>March 20</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:47. North Pole. Norwegian Sea.\r\n<strong>September 13</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. S. Africa. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2016</h3>\r\n<strong>March 9</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:09.  Sumatra, Borneo, Sulawesi, Pacific Ocean.\r\n<strong>September 1</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse.  Africa.  Indian Ocean.\r\n<h3>2017</h3>\r\n<strong>February 26</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Pacific. Chile. Argentina. Atlantic. Africa.\r\n<strong>August 21</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:40. United States.', 'Eclipse Calendar', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '551-revision-42', '', '', '2010-04-17 19:45:03', '2010-04-17 23:45:03', '', 551, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/551-revision-42', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
