(2530, 5, '2012-09-14 23:53:49', '2012-09-15 03:53:49', '<p style="text-align: center;">The Great Australian Eclipse is still a few weeks away.   Until then, you\'ll have to make do with this ...</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/Dyer_Libya_600_credit.jpg" alt="dyer libya wide credit" /></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Totality in Libya 2006 - thanks to the keen eye of Canadian astro-photographer Alan Dyer.</p>\r\n\r\n</figure>It\'s hard to say what makes the best eclipse photographs. The events are so incredibly dynamic, emotional and high contrast in nature that any favourite images are completely subjective. But in a sense, that\'s why it\'s so cool. The experience simply can\'t be captured and put away for later. But one thing is certain: some images come closer than others in doing just that. And this is one of them. As a veteran of 18 solar eclipses - and a consumer of tens of thousands of eclipse images - I can say that the truth and the excitement contained in this shot by Alan Dyer is rare. And it\'s one of my all-time faves.  I\'m keeping my fingers crossed we all get photo opportunities like this in November.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/news/total-eclipse-in-2012">Here</a> are my plans for the next total eclipse of the sun.', 'Best Eclipse Photos', 0, 'What makes a great eclipse photograph? ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'best-eclipse-photos', '', '\nhttp://eclipseguy.dev/news/total-eclipse-in-2012', '2015-06-11 12:52:22', '2015-06-11 16:52:22', '', 0, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/?p=2530', 0, 'post', '', 0),
