(2537, 5, '2012-09-14 23:44:40', '2012-09-15 03:44:40', '<p style="text-align: center;">The Great Australian Eclipse is still a few weeks away! Until then, you\'ll have to make do with this ...</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/Dyer_Libya_600_credit.jpg" alt="dyer libya wide credit" /></p>\n\n<figure>\n<p style="text-align: center;">Totality in Libya 2006 - thanks to the keen eye of Canadian astro-photographer Alan Dyer.</p>\n</figure>\nIt\'s hard to say what makes the best eclipse photographs.  The events are so incredibly dynamic, emotional and high contrast in nature that any favourite images are completely subjective.  But in a sense, that\'s why it\'s so cool.  The experience simply can\'t be captured and put away for later.  But one thing is certain: some images come closer than others in doing just that.  And this is one of them.  As a veteran of 18 solar eclipses - and a consumer of tens of thousands of eclipse images - the truth and the excitement of this shot by Alan Dyer is rare.  And it\'s one of my all-time faves.\nKeep your fingers crossed we get photo opportunities like this in November.', 'Best Eclipse Photos ', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2530-revision-v1', '', '', '2012-09-14 23:44:40', '2012-09-15 03:44:40', '', 2530, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/2530-revision-7', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2538, 5, '2012-09-14 23:44:54', '2012-09-15 03:44:54', '<p style="text-align: center;">The Great Australian Eclipse is still a few weeks away! Until then, you\'ll have to make do with this ...</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/Dyer_Libya_600_credit.jpg" alt="dyer libya wide credit" /></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Totality in Libya 2006 - thanks to the keen eye of Canadian astro-photographer Alan Dyer.</p>\r\n</figure>\r\nIt\'s hard to say what makes the best eclipse photographs.  The events are so incredibly dynamic, emotional and high contrast in nature that any favourite images are completely subjective.  But in a sense, that\'s why it\'s so cool.  The experience simply can\'t be captured and put away for later.  But one thing is certain: some images come closer than others in doing just that.  And this is one of them.  As a veteran of 18 solar eclipses - and a consumer of tens of thousands of eclipse images - the truth and the excitement of this shot by Alan Dyer is rare.  And it\'s one of my all-time faves.\r\nKeep your fingers crossed we get photo opportunities like this in November.', 'Best Eclipse Photos ', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2530-revision-v1', '', '', '2012-09-14 23:44:54', '2012-09-15 03:44:54', '', 2530, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/2530-revision-8', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2539, 5, '2012-09-14 23:47:18', '2012-09-15 03:47:18', 'Total Solar Eclipse, from a site 130 km south of Tobrouk, Libya; March 29, 2006. 0.8 second exposure with Canon 20D camera and 10-22mm lens at 12mm focal length and f/5 aperture. Exposure set auotmatically. Part of a time-lapse sequence with frames firing every 1s. \n\nVenus is visible at lower right and Mercury is barely recorded on frame half way between Venus and the Sun.', 'March 29, 2006 Total Eclipse', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'march-29-2006-total-eclipse', '', '', '2015-06-11 12:37:57', '2015-06-11 16:37:57', '', 2530, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/dyer_libya_thumb.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
