(3236, 5, '2015-06-11 12:49:20', '2015-06-11 16:49:20', '<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/st_cover1_600.jpg" alt="s&amp;t_news_cover" /></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Any fan of the sky wants to appear in the pages of Sky &amp; Telescope!</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The article in the July 2012 issue of Sky &amp; Telescope features extreme eclipse chasers and the lengths to which they will go to stand in the shadow of the Moon.  Dean Regas interviewed me about my extreme chase to South America in 2010 - an expedition that could have gone all wrong.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/QuestForTotality.pdf">Download the entire article here</a>.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="http://www.skyandtelescope.com/skytel/beyondthepage/The-Quest-for-Totality-147992355.html" target="_blank">Here is the link to the S&amp;T website - where they feature a few of my eclipse chasing videos, too</a>.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"></p>\r\n\r\n</figure>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/st_detail_600.jpg" alt="s&amp;t inside page" /></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">I am almost famous now for sure!</p>\r\n\r\n</figure>', 'Cool Article About Me in Sky & Telescope Magazine', 0, 'Extreme Eclipse Chasers in the Quest For Totality is the subject of this July 2012 article by Dean Regas from the Cincinnati Observatory.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2510-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-11 12:49:20', '2015-06-11 16:49:20', '', 2510, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/2510-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3237, 5, '2015-06-11 12:52:11', '2015-06-11 16:52:11', '', 'March 29, 2006 Total Eclipse', 0, 'Total Solar Eclipse, from a site 130 km south of Tobrouk, Libya; March 29, 2006. 0.8 second exposure with Canon 20D camera and 10-22mm lens at 12mm focal length and f/5 aperture. Exposure set auotmatically. Part of a time-lapse sequence with frames firing every 1s. \n\nVenus is visible at lower right and Mercury is barely recorded on frame half way between Venus and the Sun.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'march-29-2006-total-eclipse-2', '', '', '2015-06-11 12:52:15', '2015-06-11 16:52:15', '', 2530, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/Dyer_Libya_Wide.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(3238, 5, '2012-09-15 17:42:49', '2012-09-15 21:42:49', '<p style="text-align: center;">The Great Australian Eclipse is still a few weeks away.   Until then, you\'ll have to make do with this ...</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/Dyer_Libya_600_credit.jpg" alt="dyer libya wide credit" /></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Totality in Libya 2006 - thanks to the keen eye of Canadian astro-photographer Alan Dyer.</p>\r\n</figure>\r\nIt\'s hard to say what makes the best eclipse photographs.  The events are so incredibly dynamic, emotional and high contrast in nature that any favourite images are completely subjective.  But in a sense, that\'s why it\'s so cool.  The experience simply can\'t be captured and put away for later.  But one thing is certain: some images come closer than others in doing just that.  And this is one of them.  As a veteran of 18 solar eclipses - and a consumer of tens of thousands of eclipse images - I can say that the truth and the excitement contained in this shot by Alan Dyer is rare.  And it\'s one of my all-time faves.  I\'m keeping my fingers crossed we all get photo opportunities like this in November.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/news/total-eclipse-in-2012">Here</a> are my plans for the next total eclipse of the sun.', 'Best Eclipse Photos', 0, 'What makes a great eclipse photograph? ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2530-revision-v1', '', '', '2012-09-15 17:42:49', '2012-09-15 21:42:49', '', 2530, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/2530-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3239, 5, '2015-06-11 12:52:22', '2015-06-11 16:52:22', '<p style="text-align: center;">The Great Australian Eclipse is still a few weeks away.   Until then, you\'ll have to make do with this ...</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/Dyer_Libya_600_credit.jpg" alt="dyer libya wide credit" /></p>\r\n\r\n<figure>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Totality in Libya 2006 - thanks to the keen eye of Canadian astro-photographer Alan Dyer.</p>\r\n\r\n</figure>It\'s hard to say what makes the best eclipse photographs. The events are so incredibly dynamic, emotional and high contrast in nature that any favourite images are completely subjective. But in a sense, that\'s why it\'s so cool. The experience simply can\'t be captured and put away for later. But one thing is certain: some images come closer than others in doing just that. And this is one of them. As a veteran of 18 solar eclipses - and a consumer of tens of thousands of eclipse images - I can say that the truth and the excitement contained in this shot by Alan Dyer is rare. And it\'s one of my all-time faves.  I\'m keeping my fingers crossed we all get photo opportunities like this in November.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://eclipseguy.dev/news/total-eclipse-in-2012">Here</a> are my plans for the next total eclipse of the sun.', 'Best Eclipse Photos', 0, 'What makes a great eclipse photograph? ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2530-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-11 12:52:22', '2015-06-11 16:52:22', '', 2530, 'http://eclipseguy.dev/2530-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
